														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4866431">
									

<p><strong>Seeking Greenlights:</strong> Yes</p>
<p><strong>Page Type:</strong> SCP Article</p>
<p><strong>Page Layout (Optional):</strong> Because of reasons specified in further sections, the article would be written solely in headings, images, and footnotes; that is to say, no body text.</p>
<p><strong>Elevator Pitch:</strong> A cloud of massless, blue gas, around the size of a yoga ball, with two small discs of lighter color that mimic the appearance of cartoon-like eyes. It can move approximately walking speed in any direction, hear, understand, and speak English, and can “see” through its “eyes.” Whenever it possesses something (whether by taking it or by being given it, whether it is aware or not) that is considered to be a “body” by an unspecified dictionary (Merriam-Webster), that thing disappears.</p>
<p><strong>Central Narrative:</strong> This SCP claims to have originally been a human that was “cursed.” It acts benevolently towards humans, and it voluntarily turned itself in to the Foundation. It was found that the SCP would not willingly take the body of a human (living or dead), and would have to be forcefully “given” it for the body to disappear (i.e. “you can have this human” would not work, but “this human is yours” would). Further, if someone said “this body now belongs to the SCP,” even if the SCP was out of earshot and unaware of the body’s existence, the body would disappear. The dictionary-bound nature of the SCP was then discovered. One test found that when it was given the “flavour of this wine,” the wine became tasteless. Partway through testing, the SCP began to feel lethargic. It was found that the dictionary’s council was considering adding an additional definition to its page that would include the SCP. This was swiftly prevented, but it made the Foundation aware of a killswitch. After sufficient testing was conducted, the containment procedure was decided; a small orbital craft with 2-way audio connection. If the signal is disrupted for too long of a time, it is to be assumed it has breached containment and will be terminated immediately. Further, its existence is kept to be top-secret, and all involved personnel without sufficient authorization have been administered amnestic.</p>
<p><strong>Hook/Attention-Grabber:</strong> Unlike most overpowered villains, it has interesting limitations and abilities. Since this SCP is able to cause most things to disappear, it is incredibly dangerous. However, this same ability makes it very powerful if controlled by the foundation. It can also only to be used as a last-ditch effort, though. For example, the unexplained disappearance of SCP-682 would definitely cause some alarm and raise some questions. Thus, the Foundation would be inclined to keep it alive, but only as a last resort.</p>

